Your task is to write a Jest test case that exposes a specific mutation in a JavaScript/TypeScript project.

MUTATION DETAILS
The mutation affects the following file:
sinks/drain.js
Here is the full content of that file (shown with a <PLACEHOLDER> marker):
'use strict'

module.exports = function drain (op, done) {
  var read, abort

  // Declared here so that it captures the drain's stack trace
  var doneLackingErr
  if (!done) {
    doneLackingErr = new Error('no done callback supplied')
  }

  function sink (_read) {
    read = _read
    if(abort) return sink.abort()
    //this function is much simpler to write if you
    //just use recursion, but by using a while loop
    //we do not blow the stack if the stream happens to be sync.
    ;(function next() {
        var loop = true, cbed = false
        while(loop) {
          cbed = false
          read(null, function (end, data) {
            cbed = true
            if(end = end || abort) {
              loop = false
              if(done) done(end === true ? null : end)
              else if(end && end !== true) {
                console.warn(doneLackingErr)
                throw end
              }
            }
            else if(op && false === op(data) || abort) {
              loop = false
                 <PLACEHOLDER>

            }
            else if(!loop){
              next()
            }
          })
          if(!cbed) {
            loop = false
            return
          }
        }
      })()
  }

  sink.abort = function (err, cb) {
    if('function' == typeof err)
      cb = err, err = true
    abort = err || true
    if(read) return read(abort, cb || function () {})
  }

  return sink
}

In the original code, <PLACEHOLDER> has the value:

-                 read(abort || true, done || function () {})
In the mutated code, <PLACEHOLDER> has the value:

+                 read(abort && true, done || function () {})


YOUR TASK
Write one Jest test file that:
    1. Passes when run against the original code.
    2. Fails when run against the mutated code.
    3. Tests the behavior of the mutated file in a way that reliably detects the mutation.
The test will be saved at the following path, relative to this test-generation project’s root:
llm-cache/anthropic_claude-sonnet-4.6/temp_0.5/withoutTests/cached/artifacts/pull-stream/attempt_1/pending_category/mutant-eac3cc0/testCase.test.ts

ALLOWED LIBRARIES
You may use:
    1. Any built-in Node.js modules (e.g., fs, path, crypto, etc.).

You may not use any other third-party libraries.

Looking at the mutation, the difference is:
- Original: `read(abort || true, done || function () {})`
- Mutated: `read(abort && true, done || function () {})`

The key difference is when `abort` is falsy (undefined/null/false):
- `abort || true` evaluates to `true`
- `abort && true` evaluates to `false`/`undefined`/`null` (the falsy value of abort)

This matters when `op` returns `false` (signaling to stop the stream) but `abort` hasn't been set. In that case:
- Original: calls `read(true, ...)` - properly signals end of stream
- Mutated: calls `read(undefined, ...)` - passes undefined/falsy, which might not properly signal end

I need to create a test where `op` returns `false` to stop the drain, and verify the behavior. The `read` function will receive the abort signal - in the original it gets `true`, in the mutated version it gets `undefined` (since `abort` is undefined).

I can observe this by creating a source stream that checks what value it receives when the drain signals it to stop.

```typescript
import drain from "../../../../../../../../../../../subject_repositories/pull-stream/sinks/drain.js";

describe("drain sink - op returning false", () => {
  it("should pass a truthy abort value to read when op returns false", (done) => {
    // Track what abort value is passed to read when op returns false
    let abortValueReceived: any = "NOT_SET";

    // Create a source that records the abort signal it receives
    const source = (end: any, cb: (end: any, data?: any) => void) => {
      if (end) {
        // Record what abort value we received
        abortValueReceived = end;
        cb(end);
        return;
      }
      // Provide data
      cb(null, 1);
    };

    let callCount = 0;
    // op returns false after first item, signaling drain to stop
    const op = (data: any) => {
      callCount++;
      if (callCount >= 1) {
        return false; // Signal drain to stop
      }
      return true;
    };

    const doneCallback = (err: any) => {
      // After drain completes, check what abort value was sent to read
      // Original: abort || true = true (truthy)
      // Mutated: abort && true = undefined (falsy)
      expect(abortValueReceived).toBeTruthy();
      expect(abortValueReceived).toBe(true);
      done();
    };

    const sink = drain(op, doneCallback);
    sink(source);
  });
});
```
